{"title_page": "Bangladesh Railway Class 6400", "text_new": "{{short description|Bangladeshi class of diesel-electric locomotives}}\n{{Infobox locomotive\n| name             = Bangladesh Railway Class 6400\n| image            = Maitri Express.jpg\n| caption          = Maitri Express\n| powertype        = Diesel-electric\n| builder          = Diesel Locomotive Works, India\n| serialnumber     = 6401 - 6413\n| buildmodel       = WDM-2B, WDM-2CA\n| builddate        = 6401 - 6410 (WDM-2B): 2001; 6411 - 6413 (WDM-2CA): 2004\n| totalproduction  = 13\n| uicclass         = Co-Co\n| gauge            = 1,676 mm\n| bogies           = Alco design asymmetric cast frame trimount (Co-Co) bogies\n| wheelbase        = 42\u201d 1 \u00bc \u201c\n| over bufferbeams = 12,862 mm\n| length           = 56'2\"\n| width            = 9\u201d 4 \u00be\u201d\n| height           = 13\u201d 8 \u00be\u201d\n| axleload         = 18,800 kg\n| locoweight       = 112.8 Metric Ton\n| fueltype         = Diesel\n| fuelcap          = 5,000 Liter\n| primemover       = ALCo 16-251C\n| rpmrange         = 400-1050 RPM\n| enginetype       = Four-stroke diesel engine\n| tractionmotors   = BHEL 4906\n| cylindercount    = 16\n| gear ratio       = 65:18\n| locobrakes       = Air\n| coupling         = AAR\n| maxspeed         = 120 km/h\n| poweroutput      = 2,600 hp\n| factorofadhesion = 27%\n| operator         = Bangladesh Railway\n| operatorclass    = BED-26\n| disposition      = Active\n}}\nBangladesh Railway '''Class 6400''' is a class of [[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|broad-gauge]] [[Diesel locomotive|diesel-electric locomotives]] owned by [[Bangladesh Railway]]. Total 13 [[locomotive]]s have been manufactured by [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] (DLW), [[India]], 10 in 2001 as [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2B]] and 3 in 2004 as [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A|WDM-2CA]]. They are classified as '''BED-26''' (where '''B''' = Broad gauge, '''E''' = Diesel-electric, '''D''' = DLW and '''26''' = 26 * 100&nbsp;hp) and numbered as 6401 - 6413.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trainspo.com/class/659/|title=BR BED-26 \u2014 Trainspo|website=trainspo.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Currently all are active in service.\n\n== Details ==\nClass 6400 are 2,600 [[Horsepower|hp]] diesel-electric broad-gauge locomotives. Their model are WDM-2B and WDM-2CA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/gallery/Foreign/bangladesh/DSC03841.JPG.html?|title=DSC03841|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defence.pk/pdf/threads/railway-engines-of-different-countries.110832/page-14|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They have a [[Wheel arrangement|wheel configuration]] of [[Co-Co locomotives|Co-Co]] with [[Gear-ratio|gear ratio]] 65:18. All are fitted with [[Railway air brake|air brake]] and [[Janney coupler|AAR coupling]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2d.html|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Locomotives -- Specific classes : AC Electric|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Unlike their Indian counterparts, these locomotives do not have the [[Dynamic braking|dynamic braking system]].\n\n== Usage ==\nClass 6400 locomotives when introduced, were used prominently on high-end passenger trains like Padma Express, Silk City Express and [[Maitree Express]]. Now they are mostly used on freight trains as [[Bangladesh Railway Class 6500|Class 6500]] locomotives are used to haul most high-end passenger trains.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2]]\n* [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 6500]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2900]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2700]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2600]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2000]]\n* [[Locomotives of Bangladesh]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{train-stub}}\n{{Bangladesh-stub}}\n\n\n[[Category:Diesel-electric locomotives]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Railway]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bangladeshi class of diesel-electric locomotives}}\n{{Infobox locomotive\n| name             = Bangladesh Railway Class 6400\n| image            = Maitri Express.jpg\n| caption          = Maitri Express\n| powertype        = Diesel-electric\n| builder          = Diesel Locomotive Works, India\n| serialnumber     = 6401 - 6413\n| buildmodel       = WDM-2B, WDM-2CA\n| builddate        = 6401 - 6410 (WDM-2B): 2001; 6411 - 6413 (WDM-2CA): 2004\n| totalproduction  = 13\n| uicclass         = Co-Co\n| gauge            = 1,676 mm\n| bogies           = Alco design asymmetric cast frame trimount (Co-Co) bogies\n| wheelbase        = 42\u201d 1 \u00bc \u201c\n| over bufferbeams = 12,862 mm\n| length           = 56'2\"\n| width            = 9\u201d 4 \u00be\u201d\n| height           = 13\u201d 8 \u00be\u201d\n| axleload         = 18,800 kg\n| locoweight       = 112.8 Metric Ton\n| fueltype         = Diesel\n| fuelcap          = 5,000 Liter\n| primemover       = ALCo 16-251C\n| rpmrange         = 400-1050 RPM\n| enginetype       = Four-stroke diesel engine\n| tractionmotors   = BHEL 4906\n| cylindercount    = 16\n| gear ratio       = 65:18\n| locobrakes       = Air\n| coupling         = AAR\n| maxspeed         = 120 km/h\n| poweroutput      = 2,600 hp\n| factorofadhesion = 27%\n| operator         = Bangladesh Railway\n| operatorclass    = BED-26\n| disposition      = Active\n}}\nBangladesh Railway '''Class 6400''' is a class of [[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|broad-gauge]] [[Diesel locomotive|diesel-electric locomotives]] owned by [[Bangladesh Railway]]. Total 13 [[locomotive]]s have been manufactured by [[Diesel Locomotive Works]] (DLW), [[India]], 10 in 2001 as [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2|WDM-2B]] and 3 in 2004 as [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A|WDM-2CA]]. They are classified as '''BED-26''' (where '''B''' = Broad gauge, '''E''' = Diesel-electric, '''D''' = DLW and '''26''' = 26 * 100&nbsp;hp) and numbered as 6401 - 6413.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trainspo.com/class/659/|title=BR BED-26 \u2014 Trainspo|website=trainspo.com|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Currently all are active in service.\n\n== Details ==\nClass 6400 are 2,600 [[Horsepower|hp]] diesel-electric broad-gauge locomotives. Their model are WDM-2B and WDM-2CA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/gallery/Foreign/bangladesh/DSC03841.JPG.html?|title=DSC03841|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://defence.pk/pdf/threads/railway-engines-of-different-countries.110832/page-14|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> They have a [[Wheel arrangement|wheel configuration]] of [[Co-Co locomotives|Co-Co]] with [[Gear-ratio|gear ratio]] 65:18. All are fitted with [[Railway air brake|air brake]] and [[Janney coupler|AAR coupling]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-loco2d.html|title=[IRFCA] Indian Railways FAQ: Locomotives -- Specific classes : AC Electric|website=www.irfca.org|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> Unlike their Indian counterparts, these locomotives do not have the [[Dynamic braking|dynamic braking system]].\n\n== Usage ==\nClass 6400 locomotives when introduced, were used prominently on high-end passenger trains like Padma Express, Silk City Express and [[Maitree Express]]. Now they are mostly used on freight trains as [[Bangladesh Railway Class 6500|Class 6500]] locomotives are used to haul most high-end passenger trains.\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Indian locomotive class WDM-2]]\n* [[Indian locomotive class WDM-3A]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 6500]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2900]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2700]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2600]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway Class 2000]]\n* [[Locomotives of Bangladesh]]\n* [[Bangladesh Railway]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n[[Category:Diesel-electric locomotives]]\n[[Category:Bangladesh Railway]]\n", "name_user": "Berek", "label": "safe", "comment": "stub tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangladesh_Railway_Class_6400"}
{"title_page": "Lollipop Lust Kill", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2012}}\n{{Lead too short|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Lollipop Lust Kill\n| image               = Lollipop_Lust_Kill.jpg\n| caption             =\n| image_size          = 300\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| origin              = Toledo, Ohio\n| genre               = [[Nu metal]]\n| years_active        = 1996-2020\n| label               = [[Artemis Records]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             = [http://www.myspace.com/lollipoplustkillmusic Official MySpace site]\n| current_members     =\n| Members             = Deadgreg, Pill, Knits, Evvy Pedder, Dhuman, Killer K\n}}\n\n'''Lollipop Lust Kill''' was an American [[nu metal]] band, formed in 1996 in Toledo, Ohio.\n\n==Band history==\nLollipop Lust Kill was formed in 1996 in Toledo, Ohio<ref name=\"Lollipop Lust Kill | AllMusic\">{{cite web|title=Lollipop Lust Kill {{!}} AllMusic|url=http://allmusic.com/artist/lollipop-lust-kill-p528511/biography|accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> with the original line-up including DeadGreg, Dr. Distorto, Evvy Pedder, D. Human, and drummer Bloody Sunday. Prior to Evvy (Pedder's) 1996 induction into the fold, the band had resided under the moniker 'Candy Killers'. The name 'Lollipop Lust Kill' was derived partly from a desire by the original members to incorporate a sugar-coated, tongue-in-cheek feel to the band's name, with the 'lust kill' portion inspired randomly from a description of serial killer [[John Wayne Gacy]] in the ''Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'' as a 'lust killer' read aloud one evening by Pedder to the rest of the band. Lollipop Lust Kill was born. Bloody Sunday would be replaced by R. Cynic prior to the release of ''Motel Murder Madness'' with the departed drummer's brother Killer K. joining the band on keyboards during this time.\n\nThe band played their first show at the popular Toledo, Ohio haunt Frankies with a band named Toilet, which included future keyboardist Killer K. on guitar. They would continue to play in and around Toledo establishing a rabid and loyal fan base colloquially known as 'The Lollipop Guild'.\n\nIn 1998, Lollipop Lust Kill were finalists in Toledo WBUZ radio's \"Buzz Band Showdown\" earning them a spot on WBUZ's second local artist CD and opening a radio showcase concert, Buzzfest '98, with another Toledo-based band, Sugar Buzz. Performers included just-signed Kid Rock, Sevendust, Candlebox, [[Caroline's Spine]], Fuel and Stabbing Westward.\n\nIn 2000, Lollipop Lust Kill self-released their full-length debut, ''[[Motel Murder Madness]]'', which catapulted them into the top ten of [[MP3.com]]. Their major label debut, ''[[My So Called Knife]]'', was produced by [[Sylvia Massy]] and recorded in her haunted studio in [[Weed, California]]. Massy is known for her work with [[Tool (band)|Tool]], [[System of a Down]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] and [[Johnny Cash]]. The album featured a heavy rock re-make of [[Depeche Mode]]'s song \"[[Personal Jesus]]\". It was released by [[Artemis Records]] in June 2002, but the album was met with lukewarm sales.\n\nPrior to the release of ''[[My So Called Knife]]'' (a word-play on the show ''[[My So-Called Life]]''), drummer R. Cynic and guitarist Dr. Distorto changed their stage names to Knits and Pill respectively.\n\nIn March 2004, guitarist DeadGreg and bassist D. human announced their departure from the band, citing personal reasons. Keyboardist Killer K. would follow suit a few weeks later. The band auditioned several potential replacement bassists before settling on Jay Jay and guitarist Brian Tilse, formerly of Rob Halford's outfit Fight. The reformed band attempted to write and record a follow-up to ''My So Called Knife'' for several months, before deciding to call it quits in June 2004. Jay Jay and Tilse proceeded to start the band Glass Pipe Suicide with Knits, and they recorded some demos which were made available for free online before disbanding sometime in 2005.\n\nLLK played their final show at the popular Toledo venue Headliners on June 4, 2004. The original six members (those that comprised the band during the release of ''Motel Murder Madness'') reunited for this farewell show to the accolades of several hundred friends and fans from around the country. Perhaps in a fitting final tribute, vocalist Evvy Pedder invited the audience onto the stage to participate in the traditional closing song \"Balls Out\" 'lollipop style'. In the mayhem that ensued, a portion of the stage collapsed: a fitting testament to the violent imagery forwarded by the band made manifest.\n\nGuitarist Pill and vocalist Evvy Pedder attempted to resurrect the band with new members over the next several months, but to no avail.\n\nThe future of Lollipop Lust Kill remains in doubt. Pedder, the only remaining member, still harbors aspirations to bring their particular style of murderous musical mayhem to the masses as a solo artist. He did cut a few songs with [[Meegs]] from [[Coal Chamber]] under the project name Glass Pi\u00f1ata, but has not released anything since.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n\nNotably, LLK toured with [[Coal Chamber]], [[American Head Charge]], [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]], [[Motograter]], [[Dog Fashion Disco]] and [[Kittie]].\n\nThree members (DeadGreg, Pill, and Knits) agreed to start a new band, called They Thought We Were Strangers, and played together for the first time since the farewell show in 2004. On January 27, 2011, the group released a 4-song EP available for download.\n\n==Genre==\nTheir music is considered by many as [[alternative metal]] with [[rap metal]] and [[industrial metal]] influences. According to previous interviews, they consider themselves \"murder rock\".{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\n==Albums==\n* 1997: ''[[Candycanes and Razorblades]]'' (EP)\n* 2000: ''[[Motel Murder Madness]]''\n* 2002: ''[[My So Called Knife]]''<ref name=\"Lollipop Lust Kill Discog\">{{cite web|title=Lollipop Lust Kill Discography {{!}} AllMusic|url=http://allmusic.com/artist/lollipop-lust-kill-p528511/discography|accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n;Longest Members\n* [[Evvy Pedder]] <small>(Tom Redrup)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 vocals ''1996''\n* Pill (aka Dr. Distorto) <small>(Gary Redick)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Guitar ''1994''\n* Dead Greg <small>(Greg Dillabaugh)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Guitar ''1994''\n* D. Human <small>(Dan Nichols)</small>&nbsp;- Bass ''1994''\n* Killer K <small>(Keith Sunday)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Keyboards ''1998''\n* Knits (aka R. Cynic) <small>(Chris Tesch)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Drums ''1999''\n\n;Former Members\n* Bloody Sunday <small>(Daniel Sunday)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Drums ''1994''\n* Jay Jay &nbsp;- Bass ''2004''\n* Brian Tilse &nbsp;- Guitar ''2004''\n<ref name=\"Lollipop Lust Kill Real Names\">{{cite web|title=Lollipop Lust Kill Real Names {{!}} GeoCities|url=http://www.geocities.ws/lollipoplustkillfan/bios.html}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lollipop Lust Kill Toledo Blade\">{{cite web|title=Lollipop Lust Kill Toledo Blade {{!}} ToledoBlade|url=http://www.toledoblade.com/Music-Theater-Dance/2002/06/09/Horror-meets-heavy-metal.html}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.myspace.com/lollipoplustkillmusic Official MySpace site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American alternative metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=May 2012}}\n{{Lead too short|date=September 2009}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Lollipop Lust Kill\n| image               = Lollipop_Lust_Kill.jpg\n| caption             =\n| image_size          = 300\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| origin              = Toledo, Ohio\n| genre               = [[Nu metal]]\n| years_active        = 1996-2020\n| label               = [[Artemis Records]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             = [http://www.myspace.com/lollipoplustkillmusic Official MySpace site]\n| current_members     =\n| Members             = Deadgreg, Pill, Knits, Evvy Pedder, Dhuman, Killer K\n}}\n\n'''Lollipop Lust Kill''' was an American [[nu metal]] band, formed in 1996 in Toledo, Ohio.\n\n==Band history==\nLollipop Lust Kill was formed in 1996 in Toledo, Ohio<ref name=\"Lollipop Lust Kill | AllMusic\">{{cite web|title=Lollipop Lust Kill {{!}} AllMusic|url=http://allmusic.com/artist/lollipop-lust-kill-p528511/biography|accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref> with the original line-up including DeadGreg, Dr. Distorto, Evvy Pedder, D. Human, and drummer Bloody Sunday. Prior to Evvy (Pedder's) 1996 induction into the fold, the band had resided under the moniker 'Candy Killers'. The name 'Lollipop Lust Kill' was derived partly from a desire by the original members to incorporate a sugar-coated, tongue-in-cheek feel to the band's name, with the 'lust kill' portion inspired randomly from a description of serial killer [[John Wayne Gacy]] in the ''Encyclopedia of Serial Killers'' as a 'lust killer' read aloud one evening by Pedder to the rest of the band. Lollipop Lust Kill was born. Bloody Sunday would be replaced by R. Cynic prior to the release of ''Motel Murder Madness'' with the departed drummer's brother Killer K. joining the band on keyboards during this time.\n\nThe band played their first show at the popular Toledo, Ohio haunt Frankies with a band named Toilet, which included future keyboardist Killer K. on guitar. They would continue to play in and around Toledo establishing a rabid and loyal fan base colloquially known as 'The Lollipop Guild'.\n\nIn 1998, Lollipop Lust Kill were finalists in Toledo WBUZ radio's \"Buzz Band Showdown\" earning them a spot on WBUZ's second local artist CD and opening a radio showcase concert, Buzzfest '98, with another Toledo-based band, Sugar Buzz. Performers included just-signed Kid Rock, Sevendust, Candlebox, Caroline's Spine, Fuel and Stabbing Westward.\n\nIn 2000, Lollipop Lust Kill self-released their full-length debut, ''[[Motel Murder Madness]]'', which catapulted them into the top ten of [[MP3.com]]. Their major label debut, ''[[My So Called Knife]]'', was produced by [[Sylvia Massy]] and recorded in her haunted studio in [[Weed, California]]. Massy is known for her work with [[Tool (band)|Tool]], [[System of a Down]], [[Prince (musician)|Prince]] and [[Johnny Cash]]. The album featured a heavy rock re-make of [[Depeche Mode]]'s song \"[[Personal Jesus]]\". It was released by [[Artemis Records]] in June 2002, but the album was met with lukewarm sales.\n\nPrior to the release of ''[[My So Called Knife]]'' (a word-play on the show ''[[My So-Called Life]]''), drummer R. Cynic and guitarist Dr. Distorto changed their stage names to Knits and Pill respectively.\n\nIn March 2004, guitarist DeadGreg and bassist D. human announced their departure from the band, citing personal reasons. Keyboardist Killer K. would follow suit a few weeks later. The band auditioned several potential replacement bassists before settling on Jay Jay and guitarist Brian Tilse, formerly of Rob Halford's outfit Fight. The reformed band attempted to write and record a follow-up to ''My So Called Knife'' for several months, before deciding to call it quits in June 2004. Jay Jay and Tilse proceeded to start the band Glass Pipe Suicide with Knits, and they recorded some demos which were made available for free online before disbanding sometime in 2005.\n\nLLK played their final show at the popular Toledo venue Headliners on June 4, 2004. The original six members (those that comprised the band during the release of ''Motel Murder Madness'') reunited for this farewell show to the accolades of several hundred friends and fans from around the country. Perhaps in a fitting final tribute, vocalist Evvy Pedder invited the audience onto the stage to participate in the traditional closing song \"Balls Out\" 'lollipop style'. In the mayhem that ensued, a portion of the stage collapsed: a fitting testament to the violent imagery forwarded by the band made manifest.\n\nGuitarist Pill and vocalist Evvy Pedder attempted to resurrect the band with new members over the next several months, but to no avail.\n\nThe future of Lollipop Lust Kill remains in doubt. Pedder, the only remaining member, still harbors aspirations to bring their particular style of murderous musical mayhem to the masses as a solo artist. He did cut a few songs with [[Meegs]] from [[Coal Chamber]] under the project name Glass Pi\u00f1ata, but has not released anything since.{{Citation needed|date=September 2011}}\n\nNotably, LLK toured with [[Coal Chamber]], [[American Head Charge]], [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]], [[Motograter]], [[Dog Fashion Disco]] and [[Kittie]].\n\nThree members (DeadGreg, Pill, and Knits) agreed to start a new band, called They Thought We Were Strangers, and played together for the first time since the farewell show in 2004. On January 27, 2011, the group released a 4-song EP available for download.\n\n==Genre==\nTheir music is considered by many as [[alternative metal]] with [[rap metal]] and [[industrial metal]] influences. According to previous interviews, they consider themselves \"murder rock\".{{Citation needed|date=February 2007}}\n\n==Albums==\n* 1997: ''[[Candycanes and Razorblades]]'' (EP)\n* 2000: ''[[Motel Murder Madness]]''\n* 2002: ''[[My So Called Knife]]''<ref name=\"Lollipop Lust Kill Discog\">{{cite web|title=Lollipop Lust Kill Discography {{!}} AllMusic|url=http://allmusic.com/artist/lollipop-lust-kill-p528511/discography|accessdate=16 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Members==\n;Longest Members\n* [[Evvy Pedder]] <small>(Tom Redrup)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 vocals ''1996''\n* Pill (aka Dr. Distorto) <small>(Gary Redick)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Guitar ''1994''\n* Dead Greg <small>(Greg Dillabaugh)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Guitar ''1994''\n* D. Human <small>(Dan Nichols)</small>&nbsp;- Bass ''1994''\n* Killer K <small>(Keith Sunday)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Keyboards ''1998''\n* Knits (aka R. Cynic) <small>(Chris Tesch)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Drums ''1999''\n\n;Former Members\n* Bloody Sunday <small>(Daniel Sunday)</small>&nbsp;\u2013 Drums ''1994''\n* Jay Jay &nbsp;- Bass ''2004''\n* Brian Tilse &nbsp;- Guitar ''2004''\n<ref name=\"Lollipop Lust Kill Real Names\">{{cite web|title=Lollipop Lust Kill Real Names {{!}} GeoCities|url=http://www.geocities.ws/lollipoplustkillfan/bios.html}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Lollipop Lust Kill Toledo Blade\">{{cite web|title=Lollipop Lust Kill Toledo Blade {{!}} ToledoBlade|url=http://www.toledoblade.com/Music-Theater-Dance/2002/06/09/Horror-meets-heavy-metal.html}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.myspace.com/lollipoplustkillmusic Official MySpace site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:American alternative metal musical groups]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1996]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal musical groups from Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "Atlantic306", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkCaroline's SpineusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lollipop_Lust_Kill"}
{"title_page": "TASCAM", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n|name             = TASCAM\n|logo             = TASCAM.png\n|logo_size        = 250px\n|caption          = \n|type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n|genre            = \n|fate             = \n|predecessor      = \n|successor        = \n|foundation       = {{Start date|1971}}\n|founder          = \n|defunct          = \n|location_city    = [[Montebello, California]]\n|location_country = United States\n|locations        = \n|area_served      = Worldwide\n|key_people       = \n|industry         = [[Electronics]]\n|products         = \n|production       = \n|services         = \n|revenue          = \n|operating_income = \n|net_income       = \n|aum              = \n|assets           = \n|equity           = \n|owner            = \n|num_employees    = \n|parent           = [[TEAC Corporation]]\n|divisions        = \n|subsid           = \n|homepage         = [http://tascam.com/ tascam.com]\n|intl             = \n}}\n\n'''TASCAM''' is the professional audio division of [[TEAC Corporation]], headquartered in [[Montebello, California]]. Tascam is credited as the inventor of the [[Portastudio]], the first cassette-based [[Multitrack recording|multi-track]] home studio recorders.  Tascam also introduced the  first low-cost mass-produced multitrack recorders with Simul-Sync designed for recording musicians.  Tascam also manufactured [[reel-to-reel]] tape machines and audio mixers for home recordists from the early 1970s through the mid-1990s.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Tascam-16Track.jpg|thumb|right|250px|The TASCAM 85 16B analog tape recorder can record 16 tracks of audio on 1-inch (2.54cm) tape.]]\n[[File:TEAC 2340.jpg|thumb|right|200px|The [[TEAC Corporation|TEAC]] 2340, a popular early home multitrack recorder, four tracks on \u00bc inch tape]]\n\nTascam started out as a research and development group to research how to use TEAC's recording technology in musician and recording studio products.  The group was called TASC ('''T'''EAC '''A'''udio '''S'''ystems '''C'''orp).  The founders included Mr. K. Tani, one of the founders of TEAC-Japan and Dr. Abe, a senior TEAC-Japan engineer.  In 1971 TASCAM (TASC '''AM'''erica Corp.) was founded to distribute TASC products in the U.S.  It also conducted additional market research in the US for the Japanese parent company. The company's first headquarters was at 5440 McConnell Avenue, [[Los Angeles]], CA 90066.  In 1974 it moved its headquarters to 7733 Telegraph Road, Montebello, California.\n\nTascam's first products were TEAC brand multitrack recorders.  In 1972 it introduced the first low-cost mass-produced multitrack recorders with Simul-Sync:\n\n* The A3340 4-track recorder with 10.5\" tape reels, 7\u00bd and 15 ips speeds w/ manual direction toggle lever\n* The A2340 4-track recorder with 7\" tape reels, 3\u00be and 7\u00bd ips speeds w/ manual direction toggle lever\n* The A3340S 4-track recorder with 10.5\" tape reels, 7\u00bd and 15 ips speeds, the 's' designation indicating improved w/ solenoid control\n* The A2340S 4-track recorder with 7\" tape reels, 3\u00be and 7\u00bd ips speeds, the 's' designation indicating improved w/ solenoid control\n\nIn 1973 they introduced the first Tascam-branded products:\n\n* M-10 modular 12x4x2 mixer\n* Series 70H-X MTR\n* Series 70H-8 MTR\n\nOn March 4, 1973 TEAC merged the Tascam Corporation into TEAC Corporation of America (TCA). TEAC-Japan retains the exclusive worldwide rights to the TASCAM brand name for their professional audio related products.<ref name=\"TASCAM Forums &gt; History of TASCAM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tascamforums.com/threads/history-of-tascam.2132/ |title=A Little Tascam History Lesson |publisher=TASCAM Forums |date= |accessdate=2014-02-15}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 [[Gibson|Gibson Brands Inc.]] bought a majority stake in [[TEAC Corporation]], the parent company of TASCAM.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/03/29/gibson-teac-purchase-idUST9N0BZ01Q20130329|title=Gibson Guitar to buy TEAC, add|first=Reuters|last=Editorial|website=reuters.com}}</ref> In October 2017, TASCAM partnered with Philly punk band the Dead Milkmen and philanthropic record label The Giving Groove to sponsor a remix contest.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.musicconnection.com/tascam-giving-groove-milkmen-contest/|title=TASCAM Partners With The Giving Groove, Dead Milkmen for Contest|website=www.musicconnection.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-11-10}}</ref>\n\n==Notable and industry-recognized products==\n\n===[[Portastudio]] and pocketstudio===\n\n* 144 - 1979, World's first four-track recorder based on a standard cassette tape, 1982 Bruce Springsteen records [[Nebraska (album)|Nebraska]] Album<ref name=\"144BS\">{{cite web|url=http://tascam.com/news/display/226/ |title=News :: Bruce Springsteen's \"Nebraska\" - A PortaStudio, two SM57's, and Inspiration |publisher=TASCAM |date=2007-07-25 |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref> 2006 Mix magazine TECnology hall of fame<ref name=\"MixTec2006\">{{cite web|url=http://mixonline.com/TECnology-Hall-of-Fame/1979-teac-portastudio-090106/ |title=1979 TEAC Portastudio|publisher=Mix|date=2006-09-01|accessdate=2014-08-29}}</ref>\n[[File:Tascam Portaone.jpg|thumb|Tascam Portaone Ministudio]]\n* Porta One Ministudio - 1984, First battery-operated portable studio.\n* 388 Studio - 1985 World's first eight-track 1/4\" multitrack and mixer combination.\n* 564 - 1997 First [[MiniDisc]]-based digital Portastudio.\n* 788 - 2000 World's first 24-bit eight-track hard-disk Portastudio<ref name=\"2001SOS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/feb01/articles/tascam788.asp |title=TASCAM 788 |publisher=Sound On Sound | date=February 2001 |accessdate=2013-08-09}}</ref>\n* 2488 24-Track Hard-Drive-based digital portastudio - 2004 Music Trades Magazine Product of the Year,<ref name=\"2004MT\">{{cite web|url=http://tascam.com/news/display/173/ |title=News :: TASCAM 2488 is Music Trades' Product of the Year |publisher=TASCAM |date=2007-04-02 |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref> MIPA Desktop Recording Workstation of the Year<ref name=\"2004MIPA\">{{cite web|url=http://tascam.com/news/display/20/ |title=News :: TASCAM 2488 24-TRACK WORKSTATION garners awards |publisher=TASCAM |date= |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n* DP-02 eight-track digital recorder - 2008 Music & Sound Retailer Best New Multitrack recorder <ref name=\"PortaTM\">[http://www.trademarkia.com/portastudio-79116533.html] Portastudio Trademark</ref><ref name=\"PocketTM\">[http://www.trademarkia.com/pocketstudio-76156784.html] Pocketstudio Trademark</ref>\n\n===Audio recorders===\n\n* TASCAM 80-8 Eight-channel 1/2\" analog reel deck, TASCAM offered an external optional eight-channel dedicated DBX interface module. 1975.  2017 TECnology Hall of Fame Inductee<ref name=\"2017THOF\">{{cite web|url=https://www.tecawards.org/tecnology-hall-of-fame|title=2017 TECnology Hall of Fame Inductees |accessdate=2017-09-07}}</ref>\n* DA-50 Pro [[Digital Audio Tape|DAT]] - 1989, First US-legal DAT tape recorder with [[Serial Copy Management System|SCMS]] Copy protection.\n* MSR-24 24-track 1\" Open Reel Tape Deck - 1990 [[TEC Awards|TEC Award]] Nominee<ref name=\"1990TEC\">{{cite web |url=http://tecfoundation.com/tec/1990.html |title=The TEC Awards 1990 Winners |year=1990 |accessdate=2013-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101013233309/http://tecfoundation.com/tec/1990.html |archivedate=2010-10-13 }}</ref>\n* DA-800/24 [[Digital Audio Stationary Head|DASH]] 1990, 24-channel digital tape Recorder.<ref name=\"R2RHISTORY\">{{cite web|url=http://museumofmagneticsoundrecording.org/ManufacturersTeacTascam2.html |title=Reel to Reel Tape Recorder Manufacturers - TEAC corporation \u2022 Tascam |publisher=Museum of Magnetic Sound Recording |date=2001-07-20 |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n* [[DA-88]] DTRS (tm<ref name=\"DTRSTM\">[http://www.trademarkia.com/dtrs-74637067.html] DTRS Trademark</ref>) Eight-channel Digital Audio Recorder - 1994 TEC Award Winner,<ref name=\"1994TEC\">[http://tecfoundation.com/tec/1994.html 1994 TEC Award Winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131102141801/http://tecfoundation.com/tec/1994.html |date=2013-11-02 }}</ref> 1995 Emmy Award Winner,<ref name=\"1995Emmy\">[https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000223/1995 1995 Primetime Emmys] 1995 Primetine Emmys</ref> 1995 NAB Professional's Choice Award winner.\n* DA-30mkII DAT - 1995 TEC Award Winner<ref name=\"1995TEC\">{{cite web|url=http://tecfoundation.com/tec/1995.html |title=The TEC Awards 1995 Winners |year=1995 |accessdate=2013-08-09}}</ref>\n* DA-38 DTRS - 1997 TEC Award Winner<ref name=\"1997TEC\">{{cite web|url=http://tecfoundation.com/tec/1997.html |title=The TEC Awards 1997 Winners |year=1997 |accessdate=2013-08-09}}</ref>\n* DA-98 DTRS - 1997 PAR Excellence Award, 1998 NAB Professional's Choice Award, 1998 TEC Award Winner<ref name=\"1998TEC\">{{cite web |url=http://tecfoundation.com/tec/1998.html |title=The TEC Awards 1998 Winners |year=1998 |accessdate=2013-08-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110109102315/http://tecfoundation.com/tec/1998.html |archivedate=2011-01-09 }}</ref>\n* DA-302 DAT - 1997 World's first Dual DAT deck. 1997 PAR Excellence Award Winner.\n* DA-98HR 24-bit DTRS   - 1998 Post Magazine Best Multitrack Digital Recorder.\n* DA-45HR 24-bit DAT - World's first 24-bit DAT Recorder. 1998 PAR Excellence Award Winner, 1998 Keyboard Magazine Key Buy.\n* DA-78HR 24-bit DTRS - 1999 Pro Audio Review PAR Excellence Award, 2000 TEC award Winner<ref name=\"TEC2000\">{{cite web |url=http://tecfoundation.com/tec/2000.html |title=The TEC Awards 2000 Winners |publisher=Tecfoundation.com |accessdate=2013-08-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002145108/http://tecfoundation.com/tec/2000.html |archivedate=2012-10-02 }}</ref>\n* MMR-8 / MMR-16 eight-channel [[Hard disk recorder|Hard Disk Recorder]] - 2000 Emmy Award Winner,<ref name=\"MixMag2001\">[http://mixonline.com/news/audio_tascam_timeline_vista/ Mix Magazine May 17, 2001] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5y6Wr12L0?url=http://mixonline.com/news/audio_tascam_timeline_vista/ |date=April 21, 2011 }} Mix Magazine May 17, 2001</ref><ref>[http://www.sessioncontrol.com/about_us.htm] VP Of Engineering at Timeline Vista</ref> 2001 Oscar Scientific Award Winner.<ref name=\"2001OSCAR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000003/2001/1/|title=Academy Awards, USA (2001)|website=IMDb}}</ref>\n* MX-2424 24-channel 96&nbsp;kHz Hard Disk Recorder - 1999 PAR Excellence Award Winner, 2001 TEC Award winner.<ref name=\"TEC2001\">[http://tecfoundation.com/tec/2001.html 2001 TEC award winners] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130915034119/http://tecfoundation.com/tec/2001.html |date=2013-09-15 }}</ref>\n* DS-D98 Two-channel [[Direct Stream Digital|DSD]] Recorder based on DA-98HR - 2002 TEC Award Nominee.<ref name=\"TEC2002\"/>\n* HD-P2 Portable [[Timecode]] enabled CF card two-channel recorder - 2006 PAR Award Winner.<ref name=\"PAR2006\">{{cite web|author=on 11.02.2006 |url=http://www.radioworld.com/article/par-excellence-awards-announced/15216 |title=PAR Excellence Awards Announced |publisher=Radio World |date= |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n* DV-RA1000HD DVD and Hard-Drive-based two-Channel Master DSD Recorder - 2007 TEC Award Winner.<ref name=\"TEC2007\">{{cite web|url=http://tecfoundation.com/tec/2007.html|title=2007 TEC award winners|website=tecfoundation.com}}</ref>\n* X-48 48-channel 96&nbsp;kHz Hard Disk Recorder. - 2008 TEC Award Nominee<ref name=\"TEC2008\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tecfoundation.com/tec/08nomineestech.html |title=The TEC Awards 2008 Nominees |publisher=Tecfoundation.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-09}}</ref>\n[[File:TASCAM DR-100 mkIII digital recorder.jpg|right|thumb|200px|DR-100 mkIII]]\n* DR-100 Two-channel Hand Held Recorder - 2009 TEC Award Nominee<ref name=\"TEC2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tecfoundation.com/tec/09nomineestech.html |title=The TEC Awards 2009 Nominees |publisher=Tecfoundation.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-09}}</ref>\n* HS-P82 Eight-channel Dual CF Media Field Recorder - 2009 PAR Excellence Award,<ref name=\"2009PAR\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prosoundnetwork.com/article/2009-par-excellence-award-winners-announced/10102 |title=2009 PAR Excellence Award Winners Announced |publisher=Prosound Network |date=2009-10-20 |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>  2010 Good Design Award<ref name=\"2010GoodDesign\">{{cite web|url=http://www.g-mark.org/award/describe/37033/?locale=en |title=PORTABLE MULTITRACK FIELD RECORDER [TASCAM POTABLE MULTITRACK FIELD RECORDER HS-P82&#93; &#124; Complete list of the winners &#124; Good Design Award |publisher=G-mark.org |date=2009-12-30 |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n* DR-03 Portable Handheld Recorder - 2010 Music & Sound Retailers Best Multitrack Award<ref name=\"MSR2010\">{{cite web|url=http://www.msretailer.com/awards/photogallery.html |title=The Retailer Online |publisher=Msretailer.com |date=2011-03-15 |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n* DR-680 eight-channel portable SD card recorder - 2011 TEC Award Nominee<ref name=\"TEC2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tecfoundation.com/tec/11nomineestech.html |title=The 27th TEC Awards Nominees for Technical Achievement |publisher=Tecfoundation.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n* DR-40 Handheld four-track recorder - 2012 EM Magazine Editors Choice Awards<ref name=\"EM2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.emusician.com/gear/0769/editors-choice-awards-2012/144873 |title=Editors' Choice Awards 2012 |publisher=Emusician.com |date=2012-02-01 |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</ref>\n* DR-60D Four-track recorder for DSLR Cameras - 2013 NAB Best of Show Award<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tascam.com/news/display/919/ |title=News :: TASCAM DR-60D Announced as NAB 2013 Best of Show by Pro Sound Network! |publisher=TASCAM |date=2013-04-17 |accessdate=2013-08-06}}</re